    <!-- PANEL: FINAL WORD -->
    <div class="roma-panel" id="panel-finalword">
      <div class="final-word">
        <p class="final-word-pull">None of this is new. Everything in this book was observed first by someone who had already run out of easier answers — who had tried to hold on and been broken by the grip, who had spent enough time waiting for meaning that they eventually stopped waiting and began.</p>
        <div class="final-word-body">
          <p>These ideas survived because they worked. Not for everyone, not always, not perfectly — but enough. Enough that people from every culture, every century, in languages that share no common root, kept arriving at the same observations about the mind, about time, about the self.</p>
          <p>You will not master these tenets. You will live with them, lose them, find them again, apply them badly, apply them well, forget them at the moments you most need them, and remember them at moments you least expect to. That is not failure. That is what the practice looks like from the inside.</p>
          <p>The only thing left to do is go back out and see what they are worth.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
